Let's define our program at a very high level in terms of the paths between its types
Since we can "compose" lower-level functions into higher-level functions,
we can also "decompose" higher-level functions into lower-level functions
Thus, we can read "A" as a type that is obtained by composing other lower-level functions together.
If we pass in a value of type "1" into "f" and compose "f" and "g" together, we can get an "A"
("h" is defined by doing 'f' and then 'g'.
In other words, pass an "InputType" value into "f",
which outputs a value of the "IntermediateType."
That value then gets passed into "g",
However, a value of type "1" might also be something we obtain via lower-level functions.
If we pass in a value of type "X" into "k" and compose "k" with "m", we can get a "1"
Through this process, we can use the Types of our functions to determine WHAT we want
to accomplish at a high-level (i.e. declarative programming).
Then, we can use a top-down approach to determine HOW to do that.
Thus, many people will say, "Follow the Types."
In other words, let the Types help you break big problems down into smaller problems,
solve those smaller problems, and then compose their solutions into a solution for the bigger problem.
Once we have used Algebraic Data Types (ADTs) to model our domain's concepts,
we can then use our functions to define how one values in one Type gets mapped to another
The examples of function composition that I have shown thus far
(like the one below) are quite simple to understand.
However, there are some functions whose composition leads to very interesting results.
This is the heart of Category Theory, upon which FP is founded.
One example is the "Monad," which will be explained later in this repository.
